First, let's add 2 to both sides of the second equation:
\begin{align*}
3xy+x+y+2&=4+2\\
x+2+3xy+y+2&=6\\
\end{align*}
We can add the first equation to both sides and let that equal v, in case there are multiple v's.
\begin{align*}
x+2+3xy+y+2+v(x+y)&=6+v(x+y)\\
x+3xy+y+4+1/x+1/y&=6+5\\
v(x+y)+x+3xy+y+4&=11.
\end{align*}
Now we can replace v with the first equation.
\begin{align*}
(5)(x+y)+x+3xy+y+4&=11\\
5x+5y+x+3xy+y+4&=11\\
6x+6y+3xy&=7\\
2x+2y+xy&=\frac{7}{3}.
\end{align*}
Now we let xy=v, 2x+2y+v=7/3, V≠0.
